		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform2><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=370151"><span id=>Techpriest</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>13 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>I converted my plat to copper so I had plenty of weight to play with.&nbsp;&nbsp;I took my level 12 human monk and added 50 coins to him at a time.  Looks like I lost 1 ac per stone of weight, but at some weight changes I lost 2.  From 18 to 19 I lost 1, from 19 to 20 I lost 2 for example.  This got boring so I really put the weight on, I went up to my max, 144, which is 130 stones over 14.  I only lost 52 points.  Once encumbered we start to lose Agility, so you lose AC from that.  At least for me, as long as I stay below my max encumberance, the most I can lose is 52 points.  While it is AC, it's good to know it's not worse.  Also if I see 2 pieces of armor, one weighs 3 and has AC 10, another weighs 1 and has AC 8, I will know I can pick the second and get the same protection.  These numbers may not be your numbers, play with your weight to see how it affects you.  1 plat is 1000 copper, so you should have a readily available supply of weight.<br><br>I try to start out light (13-14) so I have room to carry loot.  I stuck the back packs (3!) in the bank and carry medicine bags (.4) which are cheap and easy to find and are the same size (8 large spots).  I trashed the heavy starting food (1 I think) and made myself rat sandwiches (.1).</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8>Posting from Nickerson, KS</td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
